1106":"1106","1018":"1018","1075 to 1079":"1076","1115":"1115","1168":"1168","1079":"1079","1133":"1133","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Bramley, Hampshire, England":"Bramley, Hampshire, England","Metz, Moselle, Alsace-Champagne-Ardenne-Lorraine, France.":"Metz, Moselle, France","Metz, Moselle, Alsace-Champagne-Ardenne-Lorraine, Dutchy of Lorraine, Holy Roman Empire":"Metz, Moselle, Grand Est, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Metz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from a short form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i>, composed of ancient Germanic <i>maht</i> ‘might, strength’ + <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from Metz in Lorraine, which took its name from a Gaulish tribe, the <i>Mediomatrici</i>; in the name of the place this became abbreviated to <i>Mettis</i>, hence the modern name.","German: from <i>Mätz</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Matthias</i> (see   Matthew  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mette","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the female personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz  ).","North German: occupational name for a miller, from Middle Low German <i>matte</i>, <i>mette</i> ‘dry measure’.","French: topographic name from Old French <i>mete</i> ‘boundary stone, boundary’ (from Latin <i>meta</i> ‘bounded estate’)."]},{"name":"Metzer","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Metz (see   Metz  ).","Dutch: occupational name for a bricklayer, Middle Dutch <i>metsere</i>."]},{"name":"Metts","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Metz  ."]},{"name":"Matthew","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."]},{"name":"Metze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Gerhard, Gernot.","German:","metronymic from a short form of the personal name <i>Mechthild</i> (see   Metz   1)."]}]},{"name":"Warin","type":"FIRST","meanings":["An old name. The same as Waring or Guerin, who came over with the Conqueror; a name probably connected with that of the Waernas or Wernas. the Varini or Verini, a people of the Elbe"],"variants":[]},{"name":"\"The","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Dorothea  , also used independently."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sheriff\"","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name or nickname from Middle English <i>shirreve</i>, <i>sher(r)eve</i>, <i>sheref(fe)</i> ‘sheriff, officer of the Crown’ (Old English <i>scīrgerēfa</i>, from <i>scīr</i> ‘shire, county’ + <i>(ge)rēfa</i> ‘reeve’), literally the reeve (i.e. steward) of a shire. Compare   Reeve  .","Muslim (mainly Nigeria, Sierra Leone, and Liberia): variant of   Sharif  . In Sierra Leone and Liberia this name is found mainly among the Mandinka people. Compare   Sirleaf  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sirleaf","meanings":["West African (Liberia): altered form of the predominantly Mandinka Muslim name   Sheriff  ."]},{"name":"Reeve","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Shreve","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Sheriff  . Compare   Shreeve  ,   Shreves  ."]},{"name":"Sherriff","meanings":["English: variant of   Sheriff  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":16,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":36,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":46,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":56,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Warin \"The Sheriff\" de Metz I was born in 1050, in Metz, Moselle, France, his father, Fulk Fitz Warrin, was 32 and his mother, de Metz, was 21. He married Aimeria de Montgomery in 1076, in Hampshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1115, in Bramley, Hampshire, England, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1050–1115":"1050–1115","1055–1133":"1055–1133","1079–1168":"1079–1168","1018–1071":"1018–1071","1030–Female":"1030–Surnud","1066":"1066","1055":"1055","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1030":"1030","1050":"1050","1071":"1071","1106":"1106","1018